<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNCIL HEARS FRIENDS, FOES OF SDG&amp;E MERGER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG JOHNSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Diego City Council members listened patiently for more than two hours 
Thursday night as opponents and proponents of San Diego Gas &amp; Electric's 
proposed merger with Southern California Edison explained their positions. 
</P>
<P>
Thursday's public hearing was one of five scheduled on the controversial 
matter. The council, which is trying to determine whether the city should 
oppose the merger, could vote at its Nov. 30 meeting. 
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, more than 50 merger proponents, most of whom live outside the 
city's borders, reiterated the utilities' claim that the merger would bring 
lower rates and improved service to San Diego County residents. Many of the 
merger proponents wore badges provided by San Diegans for the Merger, a group 
with close ties to the utilities. 
</P>
<P>
More than 30 merger opponents, many of whom belong to Utility Consumers Action 
Network, a local consumer group, repeated their oft-stated claim that electric 
rates and pollution would be increased by the merger. GREG JOHNSON 
</P>
</TEXT>
