<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE; 
</P>
<P>
ASSEMBLY PANEL OKS 1/4-CENT SALES TAX HIKE FOR QUAKE AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An Assembly committee today speedily approved a quarter-cent sales tax increase 
to finance the state's share of earthquake relief efforts, as lawmakers 
convened in the Capitol in a special legislative session. 
</P>
<P>
The Assembly Revenue and Taxation Committee approved the bill by Assemblyman 
Rusty Areias (D-Los Banos) which would raise about $800 million from the 
13-month tax increase beginning Dec. 1. The bill was sent to the Ways and Means 
Committee on a 7-1 vote. 
</P>
<P>
The committee, along with a dozen other panels from both houses, met in the 
Capitol in an atmosphere of confusion as lawmakers scrambled from hearing to 
hearing and considered hastily introduced bills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
